Pace/Milton/Avalon Area Region

Waterfront Thrift (Milton) – A mission-run thrift shop on Avalon Blvd with a huge, ever-changing selection of clothing, furniture, home goods and vintage collectibles. Customers report “fun and surprise with every visit”, finding everything from current fashion to authentic vintage treasures at bargain prices. Google Maps

Helping Hand Missions (Pace) – Faith-based nonprofit thrift on Hwy 90 that’s known for its huge inventory of donated goods. You can find “anything and everything” here – from clothes and books to furniture, knick-knacks and kitchenware – all at rock-bottom prices. The Pace location (next to Zaxby’s) is particularly popular for its friendly volunteers and bargain-hunting atmosphere. Google Maps

Helping Hand Missions (Milton) – The sister store on Stewart Street continues the same mission. It’s essentially another branch of Helping Hand Missions with similarly vast inventory (home décor, clothing, furniture, etc.) donated by the community. Shoppers praise its organized layout and the fact that proceeds support local ministries. Google Maps

Goodwill (Pace – Woodbine Road) – A well-known nonprofit thrift offering affordable clothing, housewares and furniture. The spacious Pace store draws good reviews for clean facilities and frequent sales. It’s a great place to score name-brand apparel or gently-used home goods while supporting local job programs. Google Maps

Alyssa’s (Pace) – A massive consignment warehouse on Chumuckla Hwy featuring 250+ vendor booths. This isn’t a typical thrift store – it’s more like an upscale mall of antiques, home decor, boutique clothing and furniture. Every nook is crammed with unique finds, from vintage glassware to trendy lamps, and shoppers love the friendly, Christ-centered vibe. Google Maps

Blackwater Trail Antiques & More (Milton) – A locally owned antiques and vintage consignment shop on Berryhill Street. It’s known for an eclectic mix of old and new – furniture, signs, decorative pieces and even jewelry. Reviewers note the friendly owners and well-organized booths. This hidden gem is like an antique mall in a cozy setting. Google Maps

Emilee’s Closet (Milton) – A women’s consignment boutique on Hwy 90. This small shop specializes in gently-used women’s and children’s clothing and accessories. Shoppers say it has “great clothes” at low prices and a welcoming atmosphere run by helpful local ladies. Google Maps

Lollipops Children’s Consignment (Milton) – Located on Woodbine Road, this store focuses on kids’ clothing, toys and baby gear. Parents love it for high-quality name-brand clothes at a fraction of retail. The shop is well-organized by size and season, making it easy to find like-new items for newborns through teens. Google Maps

2nd Fold Men’s Resale (Milton) – A thrift shop on Hwy 90 geared toward men’s fashion. It offers lightly-worn casual and dress clothing, shoes and accessories. Regulars praise its tidy, well-organized racks of name-brand items, plus a quirky mix of records, comics and even motorcycle gear in the same shopping area. Google Maps

Vision of Hope Thrift (Milton) – A church-run thrift on Woodbine Road (Milton United Methodist outreach). It sells donated clothing, household items and furniture at very low prices to benefit local charities. Though smaller than some big-name stores, it’s known for bargain deals and the knowledge that proceeds help those in need. Google Maps

Pensacola Metropolitan Area Region

Rusty Relic (Pensacola) – A “fun, funky, unique vintage shop” on West Navy Blvd. This locally owned store doubles as an estate liquidation gallery, packed with antiques and quirky home décor. Customers rave about its cozy vibe, well-organized displays and treasures like seashell art and retro signs. (It’s open 7 days a week and is one of Pensacola’s top-rated thrifts.) Google Maps

Teen Challenge SuperThrift (Pensacola, 9th Ave) – A large charity thrift with three Pensacola-area locations (the N. 9th Ave store is one example). It’s stocked daily with “unique finds: from retro clothing and vintage furniture to rare collectibles”. Shoppers enjoy the constantly changing inventory and affordable pricing, knowing 100% of proceeds fund addiction recovery programs. Google Maps

All About Antiques (Pensacola) – A long-established antiques mall at 3940 W. Navy Blvd. It’s actually an “antique store” in name, but offers a huge range of goods: collectibles, art, furniture, vintage toys, décor and even clothing. Visitors say the selection is incredible – from Fiesta ware to WWII memorabilia – and that the staff is extremely helpful. A must-visit for any antique lover. Google Maps

The Redemption Store (Pensacola) – A thrift ministry of Perdido Bay Methodist Church at Gulf Beach Highway. It’s run entirely by volunteers and sells donated goods at excellent prices. All inventory (furniture, clothing, household items, etc.) is donated; proceeds support local and global missions. Shoppers praise the friendly atmosphere and the fact that every purchase helps fund the church’s outreach programs. Google Maps

St. Vincent de Paul Thrift Store (Pensacola) – A Catholic charity thrift with three large locations (e.g. Chief’s Way). It offers “diverse collection of gently used clothing, furniture, appliances, books and household items – all at wallet-friendly prices”. Customers can always find a little of everything: trendy clothing, vintage knick-knacks, even kitchenware and books. Best of all, every cent of profit goes back to help struggling families and local food pantries. Google Maps

Loaves & Fishes Thrift (Pensacola) – A thrift store run by the Loaves & Fishes Soup Kitchen on North Palafox. It carries “quality low-priced items”, ranging from clothes to furniture. Patrons appreciate that all proceeds fund the charity’s feeding, sheltering and clothing programs. The store is fairly small but well-stocked with bargains; locals like to drop by often for fresh deals knowing the money helps feed Pensacola’s needy. Google Maps

UB – The Unique Boutique (Pensacola) – A stylish resale shop on West Garden Street. It specializes in an eclectic mix of gently used treasures, brand-new gift items, local artisan goods and designer women’s clothing. The front of the store is filled with home décor, art pieces and furniture, while the back room offers racks of upscale women’s fashions and accessories. It’s not your average thrift – more like an upscale consignment where everything is carefully curated at reasonable prices. Google Maps

Marcus Pointe Thrift Store (Pensacola) – A mission-driven thrift shop supporting military families and overseas missions. Run by volunteers, it sells donated household goods, toys, furniture and clothing. Every purchase directly helps local and global causes, and shoppers enjoy the rotating weekly sales. (It’s a smaller operation but highly regarded for friendly service and the “feel-good” factor of giving back.) Google Maps

Goodwill (Pensacola, Olive Road) – A large nonprofit store on East Olive Road. As part of Goodwill Gulf Coast, it stocks all the usual thrift fare: racks of clothes, electronics, furniture, and more. Reviews note the store’s helpful staff and frequent markdowns. Shopping here is a classic bargain experience, with the added bonus that purchases fund job training and community services. Google Maps

Back to the Rack (Cantonment/Pensacola) – A locally owned shop at Hwy 29 S in Cantonment (technically Pensacola address). It’s a thrift and resale store with a strong local following. Customers report very reasonable prices and an organized layout of men’s and women’s clothing, plus occasional home goods. It’s praised for a community-oriented spirit – the owners emphasize giving back through local charity drives. Google Maps

Sources: Descriptions are drawn from official thrift-store sites and local reviews and reflect current hours and inventory highlights. (All shops are open to the public as of 2025.)
